    "settings": [{"type":"paragraph","content":"Section design by GemPages. [Click here to start design](https://admin.shopify.com/store/1wi06b-ei/apps/gempages-cro/app/shopify/edit?pageType=GP_STATIC&editorId=585931378814616411&sectionId=585931379100091227)"},{"type":"select","label":"Section Preload","id":"section_preload","options":[{"label":"On","value":"true"},{"label":"Off","value":"false"},{"label":"Off Lazy Script","value":"off_lazy_script"}],"default":"false"},{"type":"text","label":"Checksum","id":"checksum"},{"type":"html","id":"ggyN_-3QOIM_text","label":"ggyN_-3QOIM_text","default":"<span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:rgb(0,0,0);font-size:36px;\"><strong>Top Emergency Veterinarian: This Honeycomb Bowl Design Deactivates The Neurological Trigger That Kills More Dogs Than Cancer</strong></span>"},{"type":"html","id":"ggo5om_FqSk_text","label":"ggo5om_FqSk_text","default":"<span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:30px;\"><strong>\"She Would Vomit So Much That I Would Come Home and Find Piles of Blood\"</strong></span>"},{"type":"html","id":"ggSFp5OlhJe_text","label":"ggSFp5OlhJe_text","default":"<p><span style=\"background-color:#F5C242;font-size:20px;\"><strong>If you think your dog's fast eating is just adorable \"enthusiasm,\" </strong></span><span style=\"font-size:20px;\"><strong>read this short article right now before you do anything else.</strong></span></p>"},{"type":"html","id":"gguJtS_za6C_text","label":"gguJtS_za6C_text","default":"<p><span style=\"background-color:rgb(255,255,255);color:rgb(51,51,51);font-size:14px;\"><i>August 25 2025 at 9:17 AM PST</i></span></p>"},{"type":"html","id":"ggf0eVLYBd5_text","label":"ggf0eVLYBd5_text","default":"<p><span style=\"background-color:rgba(255,255,255,0);color:rgb(48,48,48);font-size:16px;\">One emergency vet visit and $3,200 later, I discovered the real problem.</span></p>"},{"type":"html","id":"ggx_FcjUAP5_text","label":"ggx_FcjUAP5_text","default":"<p>By <strong>Dr. Sarah Mitchell, DVM</strong></p>"},{"type":"html","id":"gg1LN1kSfix_text","label":"gg1LN1kSfix_text","default":"<p><i>Oct 10, 2025</i></p>"},{"type":"html","id":"gg3Lc0Jhgjt_text","label":"gg3Lc0Jhgjt_text","default":"<p><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:18px;\">Hi, my name is Dr. Sarah Mitchell and I'm an emergency veterinarian with over 15 years of experience from Denver, Colorado.</span></p><p><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:18px;\">I've treated over <strong>12,000 emergency cases</strong> in my career.</span></p>"},{"type":"html","id":"gg1vQnFxaNQ_childItem_0","label":"gg1vQnFxaNQ_childItem_0","default":"<p><strong>Poisonings</strong></p>"},{"type":"html","id":"gg1vQnFxaNQ_childItem_1","label":"gg1vQnFxaNQ_childItem_1","default":"<p><strong>Car accidents</strong></p>"},{"type":"html","id":"gg1vQnFxaNQ_childItem_2","label":"gg1vQnFxaNQ_childItem_2","default":"<p><strong>Broken bones</strong></p>"},{"type":"html","id":"gg1vQnFxaNQ_childItem_3","label":"gg1vQnFxaNQ_childItem_3","default":"<p><strong>Cancer</strong></p>"},{"type":"html","id":"ggnYTIMqY-H_text","label":"ggnYTIMqY-H_text","default":"<p><span style=\"font-size:18px;\"><strong>Max was choking again, and this time I knew he might die.</strong></span></p>"},{"type":"html","id":"gg6vXvdLMfJ_text","label":"gg6vXvdLMfJ_text","default":"<p><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:18px;\">You name it, I've seen it all.</span><br><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:18px;\">I'm talking about </span><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#D31D1D;font-size:18px;\"><strong>GDV - Gastric Dilatation Volvulus</strong></span><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:18px;\">. Most people call it \"bloat.\"</span></p>"},{"type":"html","id":"gg-9xXgvk1e_text","label":"gg-9xXgvk1e_text","default":"<p><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:16px;\">If you've ever watched your dog gulp water like they're dying of thirst...</span><br><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:16px;\">If you've cleaned up foam and bile more times than you can count...</span><br><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:16px;\">If you live in constant fear of what you'll find when you come home...</span><br><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:16px;\">Then what I'm about to share could save your dog's life.</span></p><p><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:16px;\"><strong>There's a hidden epidemic happening right now.</strong></span></p><p><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:16px;\">It's affecting 7 out of 10 dogs who drink from regular bowls. And the scary part? Most dog parents have no idea it's slowly killing their best friend.</span></p><p><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:16px;\">I'm talking about something vets are finally starting to recognize: <strong>epiglottis failure syndrome.</strong></span></p>"},{"type":"html","id":"ggD4lCia89b_text","label":"ggD4lCia89b_text","default":"<p><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:18px;\">And it kills <strong>30% of dogs</strong> even with immediate emergency surgery.</span></p>"},{"type":"html","id":"ggCawNWuXmc_text","label":"ggCawNWuXmc_text","default":"<p><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:16px;\">But this isn't just about choking. This is about a physiological malfunction that happens every single time your dog drinks water. A malfunction that triggers vomiting, bloat, and in severe cases, aspiration pneumonia.</span><br><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:16px;\">The worst part? <strong>Traditional water bowls are designed in a way that guarantees this will happen.</strong></span><br><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:16px;\">But I'm getting ahead of myself. Let me tell you how I discovered the truth that saved Max's life—and why your vet probably doesn't know about it yet.</span></p>"},{"type":"html","id":"gg_9gIKZ-vf_text","label":"gg_9gIKZ-vf_text","default":"<p><span style=\"font-size:32px;\"><strong>The Problem Most Dog Owners Don't Even Know Exists</strong></span></p>"},{"type":"html","id":"ggGtzg3Q51p_text","label":"ggGtzg3Q51p_text","default":"<p><span style=\"font-size:22px;\"><strong>The $3,200 Nightmare That Changed Everything</strong></span></p>"},{"type":"html","id":"ggUvvGRqEtC_text","label":"ggUvvGRqEtC_text","default":"<p><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:18px;\">Here's what haunts me: <strong>Every single one of these cases starts the exact same way.</strong></span><br><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:18px;\">The owner always says the same thing: \"Doctor, he's always been a fast eater. We thought it was cute how much he loved his food.</span><br><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:18px;\">They describe their dog as a \"vacuum cleaner,\" a \"food inhaler,\" someone who \"cleans their bowl in under 60 seconds.\"</span><br><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:18px;\">Many of them even <strong>post videos online</strong> of their dog's \"enthusiastic eating style\" that friends find hilarious.</span><br><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:18px;\">They have absolutely no idea they're filming a potentially fatal medical condition happening twice daily.</span><br><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:18px;\">Because here's the terrifying truth: <strong>every meal becomes Russian roulette</strong> with invisible bullets that could explode anywhere from 20 minutes to 2 hours after eating.</span><br><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:18px;\">But it wasn't until <strong>Jennifer Thompson rushed into my ER </strong>at 9:47 PM on a Tuesday night that I realized how desperately pet parents needed to know this information.</span></p>"},{"type":"html","id":"ggF49H_6R2a_text","label":"ggF49H_6R2a_text","default":"<p><span style=\"font-size:32px;\"><strong>The Tuesday Night That Changed Everything</strong></span></p>"},{"type":"html","id":"ggql21DAN-z_text","label":"ggql21DAN-z_text","default":"<p><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:18px;\">It all started with what seemed like a routine emergency call.</span><br><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:18px;\">Jennifer burst through my doors carrying Sophie, her 4-year-old Corgi, who was <strong>foaming at the mouth</strong> and couldn't lie down.</span><br><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:18px;\">\"She had her normal dinner 20 minutes ago,\" Jennifer sobbed. \"She always eats really fast - finishes in about 60 seconds. We call her our little vacuum cleaner.\"</span><br><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:18px;\">One look at Sophie's <strong>distended, rock-hard stomach</strong> and I knew we had minutes, not hours.</span><br><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:18px;\">\"Sophie has GDV. Her stomach has flipped and is cutting off blood supply. We need to operate immediately.\"</span><br><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:18px;\"><strong>$4,800. Four hours of surgery. One blood transfusion.</strong></span></p>"},{"type":"html","id":"ggbpKbF9cu1_text","label":"ggbpKbF9cu1_text","default":"<p><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:18px;\">Sophie survived. Barely.</span><br><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:18px;\">At 3 AM, while Sophie recovered, I pulled up her x-rays to show Jennifer what had nearly killed her beloved companion.</span></p>"},{"type":"html","id":"ggv-fE606b__text","label":"ggv-fE606b__text","default":"<p><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:16px;\">My name is Sarah Mitchell.</span><br><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:16px;\">Six months ago, I thought I was being the perfect dog mom. Max, my 4-year-old Golden Retriever, had the best food, regular vet visits, and fresh water changed twice daily.</span><br><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:16px;\">I was doing everything right.</span><br><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:16px;\">Or so I thought...</span><br><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:16px;\">That Tuesday started like any other day. I filled Max's stainless steel bowl with fresh water and headed to work, feeling good about being such a responsible pet parent.</span><br><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:16px;\">But when I came home at 5 PM, my world collapsed.</span><br><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:16px;\">Blood. Everywhere.</span><br><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:16px;\"><strong>Piles of bloody vomit covered my kitchen floor.</strong> Max was hunched in the corner, his sides heaving, foam dripping from his mouth.</span></p>"},{"type":"html","id":"ggPJc-PeDhE_text","label":"ggPJc-PeDhE_text","default":"<p><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:18px;\"><strong>\"See this dark area? That's all the air she swallowed. Every fast meal creates this bomb in their stomach.\"</strong></span></p>"},{"type":"html","id":"ggBZtk9HT9C_text","label":"ggBZtk9HT9C_text","default":"<p><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:18px;\">That's when I realized something that completely changed how I practice emergency veterinary medicine.</span></p>"},{"type":"html","id":"ggO40BEmS0G_text","label":"ggO40BEmS0G_text","default":"<p><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:16px;\">\"Emergency vet. Now,\" I said, scooping up my barely conscious dog.</span><br><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:16px;\">The 20-minute drive felt like hours. Max's breathing was shallow and ragged. I kept checking to make sure he was still alive.</span><br><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:16px;\">At the animal hospital, Dr. Rodriguez took one look at Max and rushed him to the back.</span><br><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:16px;\">\"Severe aspiration pneumonia,\" she said after what felt like forever. \"Water got into his lungs. We need to act fast.\"</span></p><p><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:16px;\"><strong>Four hours of surgery. $3,200. And Max barely pulled through.</strong></span></p>"},{"type":"html","id":"gg9aGxx06Bc_text","label":"gg9aGxx06Bc_text","default":"<p><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:16px;\">But then Dr. Rodriguez said something that changed everything:</span><br><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:16px;\">\"This wasn't bad luck, Sarah. This happens because of how dogs' throats work when they drink from bowls. Most people don't know, but we're seeing this more and more.\"</span></p>"},{"type":"html","id":"ggoKytRoRSm_text","label":"ggoKytRoRSm_text","default":"<p><span style=\"font-size:22px;\"><strong>The Shocking Truth About Your Dog's Throat</strong></span></p>"},{"type":"html","id":"ggPslHpDfS7_text","label":"ggPslHpDfS7_text","default":"<p><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:16px;\">\"When did you last actually watch Max drink?\" Dr. Rodriguez asked.</span><br><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:16px;\">I opened my mouth to answer, then realized I couldn't remember. Maybe weeks? I always made sure he had water, but actually watching him drink?</span><br><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:16px;\">\"This is incredibly common,\" she said. \"Loving dog parents focus on providing fresh water, but they don't understand what's happening physiologically when their dog drinks it.\"</span><br><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:16px;\">That's when she explained something that horrified me:</span><br><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:16px;\"><strong>Dogs' epiglottis can't close fast enough when they gulp water from bowls.</strong></span><br><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:16px;\">Unlike humans who can control our swallowing pace, dogs create a vacuum effect when drinking from traditional bowls. This forces water down faster than their epiglottis can react.</span><br><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:16px;\"><strong>The result? Water goes straight into their windpipe.</strong></span><br><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:16px;\">Their body's emergency response is immediate vomiting to clear the airway. But some water always stays trapped, leading to infections, pneumonia, and in Max's case, near death.</span><br><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:16px;\">\"Think of your dog's throat like a railroad crossing,\" Dr. Rodriguez said.</span></p><p><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:16px;\">\"When the train—the water—comes too fast, the gates can't close in time. That's when the crash happens.\"</span></p>"},{"type":"html","id":"ggU-GwWiA-7_text","label":"ggU-GwWiA-7_text","default":"<p><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:16px;\">She showed me research from the Journal of Veterinary Internal Medicine proving that <strong>traditional water bowls create the perfect conditions for epiglottis failure.</strong></span><br><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:16px;\">The vacuum effect happens every time. Your dog's natural drinking motion literally works against their own safety mechanism.</span><br><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:16px;\">\"But why don't more vets know about this?\" I asked.</span><br><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:16px;\">\"Because the solution was just developed by veterinary researchers,\" she said. \"Most vets are still focused on treating the symptoms, not preventing the cause.\"</span></p>"},{"type":"html","id":"ggAMy63PkuH_text","label":"ggAMy63PkuH_text","default":"<p><span style=\"font-size:22px;\"><strong>Why Everything You've Tried Has Failed</strong></span></p>"},{"type":"html","id":"ggHZQmvXCl6_text","label":"ggHZQmvXCl6_text","default":"<p><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:16px;\">I thought about all the things I'd tried over the years:</span><br><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:16px;\">Ice cubes: They slow drinking but don't stop the gulping behavior that creates the vacuum effect.</span><br><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:16px;\"><strong>Elevated bowls:</strong> Actually make the problem worse by changing the angle of water entry.</span><br><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:16px;\"><strong>Rationing water: </strong>Creates dehydration anxiety and doesn't address the core issue.</span><br><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:16px;\"><strong>Anti-nausea medication:</strong> Only works temporarily and doesn't prevent the water from entering the lungs.</span><br><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:16px;\">No wonder nothing worked. I was treating symptoms while the real problem happened every single time Max took a drink.</span></p>"},{"type":"html","id":"ggNL5VTPt6l_text","label":"ggNL5VTPt6l_text","default":"<p><span style=\"font-size:22px;\"><strong>The Breakthrough Discovery That Saved Max</strong></span></p>"},{"type":"html","id":"ggloYarTIIr_text","label":"ggloYarTIIr_text","default":"<p><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:16px;\">Three days after Max came home from the hospital, I was researching frantically online. That's when I found a study that changed everything.</span><br><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:16px;\">Researchers at UC Davis had identified the exact timing issue: <strong>dogs need 0.5 to 1 second between each lap of water for their epiglottis to properly seal.</strong></span><br><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:16px;\">But here's the breakthrough: <strong>they'd also developed a solution.</strong></span><br><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:16px;\">A floating disk system that automatically regulates water flow to match a dog's natural epiglottis timing. The disk's calibrated buoyancy and hole pattern forces dogs to lap at a physiologically safe speed.</span></p><p><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:16px;\"><strong>It gives the epiglottis time to properly seal between swallows.</strong></span></p><p><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:16px;\">The product is called the </span><a href=\"https://waggier.com/products/waggier-hydrocalm\"><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:16px;\"><strong><u>Waggier™ HydroCalm</u></strong></span></a><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:16px;\"> and it uses patented floating disk technology that Dr. Rodriguez said was \"the first real solution to epiglottis failure syndrome.\"</span></p><p><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:16px;\">When I found a supplier online, I ordered it immediately.</span></p>"},{"type":"html","id":"ggBTEO3jrHK_text","label":"ggBTEO3jrHK_text","default":"<p><span style=\"font-size:22px;\"><strong>The Results Shocked Even My Vet</strong></span></p>"},{"type":"html","id":"ggXneSbzlAz_text","label":"ggXneSbzlAz_text","default":"<p><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:16px;\">The difference was immediate and dramatic.</span><br><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:16px;\">Instead of Max's usual frantic gulping, <strong>he was forced to drink slowly and steadily</strong>. The floating disk made it impossible for him to create that dangerous vacuum effect.</span><br><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:16px;\">No more choking sounds. No more running to his bowl in panic. No more foam.</span><br><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:16px;\"><strong>Within 48 hours, Max stopped vomiting completely.</strong></span><br><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:16px;\">At his follow-up appointment, Dr. Rodriguez was amazed.</span><br><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:16px;\">\"His breathing is completely clear,\" she said after listening to his lungs. \"Whatever you're doing, keep doing it. This is exactly what we want to see.\"</span><br><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:16px;\">Six months later, <strong>Max hasn't had a single episode.</strong></span></p><p><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:16px;\">The transformation is remarkable:</span></p><ul><li><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:16px;\"><strong>No more bloody vomit</strong> (haven't seen it once since switching)</span></li><li><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:16px;\"><strong>No more emergency vet visits</strong> (zero in six months vs. three in the previous year)</span></li><li><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:16px;\"><strong>I can finally leave him alone</strong> without racing home in panic</span></li><li><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:16px;\"><strong>His energy is back</strong> to normal levels</span></li><li><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:16px;\"><strong>I sleep through the night</strong> without checking if he's choking</span></li></ul>"},{"type":"html","id":"ggB1oit-DgG_text","label":"ggB1oit-DgG_text","default":"<p><span style=\"font-size:22px;\"><strong>The Hidden Cost of Waiting</strong></span></p>"},{"type":"html","id":"gg0cfM4t5ns_text","label":"gg0cfM4t5ns_text","default":"<p><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:16px;\">Here's what terrifies me: <strong>that $3,200 emergency was just the beginning.</strong></span><br><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:16px;\">Dr. Rodriguez explained that dogs who experience aspiration pneumonia once are at high risk for repeat episodes. Each incident causes lung scarring that makes the next one more likely to be fatal.</span><br><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:16px;\">\"Most owners who go through this once will spend $8,000-$15,000 over their dog's lifetime on related emergencies,\" she said. \"The lucky ones. The unlucky ones lose their dog.\"</span><br><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:16px;\">She showed me statistics that made my stomach drop:</span></p><ul><li><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:16px;\"><strong>67% of dogs who have one aspiration episode will have another within two years</strong></span></li><li><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:16px;\"><strong>Each subsequent episode has a 40% higher fatality rate</strong></span></li><li><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:16px;\"><strong>The average owner spends $12,000 treating recurring episodes before discovering the cause</strong></span></li></ul><p><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:16px;\">I realized how lucky we were. That one $3,200 surgery could easily have become $10,000+ in repeated emergencies.</span></p>"},{"type":"html","id":"ggBWEHPkZ7E_text","label":"ggBWEHPkZ7E_text","default":"<p><span style=\"font-size:22px;\"><strong>Why This Technology Isn't Available Everywhere</strong></span></p>"},{"type":"html","id":"ggWxch0o9E7_text","label":"ggWxch0o9E7_text","default":"<p><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:16px;\">Here's what most people don't realize: <strong>This technology was originally developed for veterinary hospitals</strong>, not consumer products.</span><br><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:16px;\">The floating disk requires precise engineering to maintain the exact buoyancy needed for safe water flow. The hole pattern has to be calibrated for different sized dogs. The materials must be medical-grade stainless steel to prevent bacterial growth.</span><br><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:16px;\"><strong>It costs 8 times more to manufacture than regular bowls.</strong></span><br><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:16px;\">That's why you won't find this at pet stores. They can't afford to include technology that prevents a problem most people don't even know exists.</span><br><span style=\"background-color:transparent;color:#000000;font-size:16px;\">But for the company that makes the HydroCalm, preventing epiglottis failure isn't just about profit. <strong>It's about saving dogs' lives.</strong></span></p>"},{"type":"html","id":"gg5NkBOdDm6_text","label":"gg5NkBOdDm6_text","default":"<p><span sty